COMMENTS__C: The rules of non-clear bags to bring inside vary widely based on who is working for Monterrey that day.
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: Aside from Pilsen Taqueria, the food is well below all other Chicago stadiums. They are often out of a majority of fountain sodas and the food is cold and not fresh. I find most of the options food I would not buy if I wasn't trapped in the stadium, and I am not a picky or healthy eater. Items like the polish or pulled pork sandwich sound good but the quality is well below your average Chicago hot dog stand,
MERCHANDISE_COMMENTS__C: I love the unique offerings like the Championship ring sweatshirt and other Fire specific offerings. The fanactics online shop is very generic and rarely offers new items. Template adidas items that are available for all teams are not as attractive. The in stadium merchandise is a good experience with much friendlier staff than the concessions, it also often offers good sales which is appreciated.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: I enjoy the matchday atmosphere and the Chicago Fire are a big part of my life.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: I would appreciate included Open Cup and leagues cup tickets much more than an improved gift or parking related improvements.

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: I have parked typically in the Waldron Parking Deck before matches since I've been a season ticket holder (since 2020), which has been great. I'm looking forward to the season ticket holder complementary parking in 2024, but hope that there is the right logistics plan in place and well communicated pre-match to deliver on this new perk - looking forward to it!
COMMENTS__C: I've had a pretty easy time getting into the stadium for most matches. Even for the Chicago Miami match this past season with a packed house, my friends and I had no problems getting into the stadium and to our seats.
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: I typically go into the Midway or nearby concessions for food / beverages. Specifically for the Midway, it usually has a significant line during halftime of the more busy matches with only one or two bartenders for all of the season ticket holders that have access to the Midway on match days. (Also, last year they didn't have Hazy Pitch until a few games into the season even though it was being sold in other locations around the stadium. I'd have to go hunting for  Hazy Pitch, along with many, many other season ticket holders that were surprised it wasn't yet stocked in the Midway).
LONG_TEXT_1__C: I think the Fire gameday experience is great! It's an all encompassing thing for me including the easy parking, gate access, special events, season ticket holder areas (like the Midway), seats close to the action, and game day environment.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: I was able to bring a bunch of my family and friends to a match last year purchasing an allotment of tickets through Marina, great experience working with the Fire account rep team (as always!). Kudos to Marina for always being helpful with any questions I send her way!

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: From last year - parking is expensive, but location is great especially on bad weather days and we can park on the north lot.  For the biggest games of the year it feels like they fail the stress test of more than usual cars (Chichirrito or Messi coming to town).  Last thing that's a bother is the entrance from Columbus coming from the North Side onto the main road to enter the stadium between the stadium and Field museum is sometimes blocked off and sometimes not.  I never know when I can or can't use it.  If it's blocked I'm forced to go South on Lake Shore Drive and loop all the way back around for a 3 mile detour and probably an extra 20 min of added time.  Either have it open or closed all the time so I know how to get there from 90 on the North Side.

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: I know parking will be free for members but having spent $33 per match last season I'm still marking the parking value as strongly dissatisfied. COMMENTS__C: It's improved, a lot. At the start of the season it was real stop start, now it's become real efficient, holding your belongings up and scan your ticket
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: You get a strongly dissatisfied for marking that Hazy Pitch up to $16 bucks a can you greedy fucks, a fucking 4 pack is like 10 bucks anywhere else, nope, not a Fire match, it was $11 but when Inter Miami stops by we're gonna secretly raise it to $16 and keep it that way.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: I love soccer. 2023 was my first time ever going to a Fire match. I bought season tickets on a whim without ever having attended a match before. I actually really kinda like soldier field. Soccer is going to explode in the US, the Fire, they're not ever gonna be Champs again, probably not in my lifetime (I'm 43) but someone's gotta support them. I also really like to point out I drive down from Wisconsin every match day. I know long commutes for match day aren't exclusive to me, but I didn't miss a home match at all last season, it's two hours one way for me, I do really love the Fire. Also, I would honestly KILL for a dedicated Fire Only stadium, I know the logistics for it are probably insane, but if in dreaming out loud here I want a modern stadium like that shitty team over in st louis and those fuckers in Nashville.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: Bring the prices of Hazy Pitch down, WTF!!! Also, a need a good Fire coffee mug, preferably red.

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: Soldier Field is a very difficult/poor experience driving & parking venue. At current Fire attendance #s, it is OK, generally. It becomes worse the bigger the attendance.  This should not be considered to be a good trade-off for customers. The offer to cover the parking cost is very appreciated. Think about it - it costs me more to park than the ticket to attend!
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: I feel ripped off for the cost of a beer. The food is very expensive for the poor quality of most of the selections. The 20% discount results in no value to me, because of the poor overall quality for the price!
LONG_TEXT_1__C: My belief that the poor quality of the Fire teams can't last for another year!  That belief has not served me well for 11 of the last 14 seasons!
LONG_TEXT_2__C: The games have become so frustrating to endure! The quality of the experience has become unsatisfactory because of the teams' overall noncompetitive performance versus the league. After 26 seasons, I'm very disappointed in the value versus the quality of the experience. Its not fun!

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: I always park in South Loop and take pedestrian bridge over the tracks to the stadium since parking is too chaotic and too expensive. For the Messi game I was going with several friends so I bought a parking ticket and when I got to the lot I was told they oversold the lot. I had to turn around and park in the south loop and missed most of the first half. While I know this is not directly the Fire's fault, it is an absolute joke that the Fire did nothing to remedy this situation with their fans, both longtime and casual. How many first time fans will never give the Fire another chance because they missed the entire game due to the 3rd party company OVERSELLING the lots?
COMMENTS__C: This should change next year with the members only entrance, but security has no idea what they are doing. They are too busy stealing giveaways to do their jobs properly.
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: I do not drink alcohol so I fill out the form to get the free drink every home game. At every single game this year when I would go to cash in my free drink and hand the worker the ticket, they would have to call multiple managers over before someone knew how to honor it. Twice I had MANAGERS tell me I was trying to scam them and that I had a fake coupon for the free drink. Again, I know these are not Fire employees, but I have never had that issue at Bears games when cashing in the free drink ticket. And to literally have managers call me a liar to my face is not alright. Do the Fire have any control over these 3rd party employees?
LONG_TEXT_1__C: Even though this team has sucked for a decade, I still love them.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: If you read one thing from my survey then read this. PLEASE stop making false promises to STHs on their benefits. I am still owed multiple experiences from the last several seasons starting with 2020. Don't make promises to your most loyal members that you can't keep. I am only being this harsh and blunt because I love this team and want to see it be successful both on and off the field, but this organization has been majorly failing since the move back to SF in 2020.

COMMENTS__C: "Communication at entrance could be better. I know changing things up is seen as enhancing security, but especially early in the season there were different ""policies"" in place for every game: about taking things out of pockets or not, putting them in try next to metal detector or not, etc. Introduction of self-scanning of tickets was a good addition that made things a lot faster. Especially with COVID still around, having a system to invite ticket takers to handle my phone was a pretty big negative compared to having paper tickets they never needed to touch. (I still miss paper tickets.)"
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: I'd like to see some draft craft beer options and more, better vegetarian food options. Beer prices especially should be at least a little bit lower. Wait time before kickoff was pretty good generally, and wait time at other times improved throughout 2023.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: Inertia and/or I still have some hope.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: "Why are we now ""Season Ticket MEMBERS""? Membership suggests e.g. a vote or ""ownership.""   Why don't all season ticket members get free bike valet? Could that be added as a benefit?  I'd love to see the club sponsor or subsidize some away trips for season ticket members and other supporters, whether or not our regular seats are in the supporters section. I've had the sense the 2020 season that the club is keen to try and limit the definition of ""supporters"" to only those with season tickets in particular standing sections. One of the best ways to turn customers into supporters is to get them to away trips. Even though it was a Section 8-organized trip, the Chicago Fire promoted the 2007 away game trip to Columbus in the stadium. It was a critical game (the Wanchope goal!) and so many people went, and so many of them became supporters for life (myself included and many of my supporter friends).   Two benefits I love that were not mentioned above are 1) the season ticket members-only barâ€”that really cuts down on time in drinks linesâ€”and 2) the Apple MLS Season Passâ€”that's great for watching away games and keeping up with what's going on around the league. I wish there were a regular home announcing team audio available for all of these games.  The 2023 Member gift: a scarf is a great thing in theory, but I don't love these. Something exclusive and celebrating the 2023 season would have been great. Something advertising me as a ""Season Ticket Member"" is not that. Special scarf is great, but don't make it about the person wearing it."

LONG_TEXT_2__C: 1. Bring back better bike parking; 2. we requested to have our season tickets split between our accounts (one ticket per account instead of two on one account that required a transfer every game) and there was no follow-through on this request; 3. parking benefit is minimal benefit for me as I take public transit (Metra) or bike to every game; 4. season ticket holder gifts are never items I'm interested in keeping/wearing; 5. ticket transfer to other games is by far the best perk; 6. I am having regret at renewing season tickets in light of no changes to the front office -- if the team continues to lose then there is no value in being a STH when I can get tickets on the secondary market for 40% of what I paid; 7. I'd like to see more efforts to improve the atmosphere through bringing in new fans -- cheaper/free community tickets benefit all fans and the team; 8. the decision to change season ticket memberships to default to auto-renew is a very bad decision and borderline unethical -- my ST rep explained that this is similar to a Netflix subscription, which insulting -- a renewal should be an active decision as opposed to a non-renewal being the active decision -- this was buried in the small print during this year's renewal process and I was made aware of the change via Reddit;

COMMENTS__C: I walk to every game from Lake Shore East Park. Is there a better way to utilize the routes from north millennium park and the Roosevelt CTA station? Perhaps somehow getting vendors/food trucks/pregame tailgate prehaps at the areas marked Arvey Field or the Great Ivy Lawn on Google Maps? This would break up the walk from the CTA station, provide a potential touch point for people just enjoying the park to get familiar with the Fire, and would improve the pregame atmosphere on the north side of Soldier Field
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: I go to 10-20 Hawks Games a year and the variety of Food and Drinks available at Soldier Field is very lacking compared to whatâ€™s offered at the United Center. Furthermore specifically for the pizza the portion is just not worth the price. Iâ€™ve been to many sporting events and often you can get a whole mini pizza for that price not a tiny slice.
MERCHANDISE_COMMENTS__C: Expand the team shop space it can pretty cramped in there. Additionally expand the variety of merchandise offered the offerings can become similar. Perhaps offer merch at like 3 different price points affordable, standard, and luxury. You could improve the quality of material used with each price point. Additionally itâ€™d be cool if there were more collectibles/signed memorabilia/etc offered. Additionally a nice fan perk could offering the option to buy merch at the stadium and have it shipped to their homes.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: Value and I enjoy watching Soccer and supporting my hometown team.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: A point about the family friendly atmosphere. The fire should create a family friendly section like the supporters section. This would create an option for those who are seeking a more family friendly experience, while maintaining a more standard experience and the more intense supporters section experience. Itâ€™s good to have as many options as possible so fans create and tailor the best possible experience for each person. Additionally work more the all of the Supporters Groups to build community and improve the gameday atmosphere. There should be more Tifos, Chanting, and smoke next year. Since we are the Fire the team should shoot up flames behind the supporters section goal, kinda like the Chicago Wolves do when announcing their starting roster.

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: The only problem I had with parking in 2023 was using the south lot for the Oct 5th game took a long time 45 minutes to get out of the parking lot due to Sector Latino not making way for cars (drinking in the parking lot) to get out and the security doing nothing. On a standard night in the North Garage it takes about 10 minutes to leave which is more acceptable. Milwaukee West is difficult if you miss the 10:40 train then you need to wait until the 12:40 train which gets you home late.
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: Prices are very high inside the stadium versus other venues for soccer.
MERCHANDISE_COMMENTS__C: Since they changed the main store to be tables that you walk up to, you do not have the opportunity to feel and see the merchandise anymore.   My largest issue was the last game I wanted to get a Sting/Fire T shirt which was on special, waited in line for 20 minutes to find out when I got to the table they were all sold out. This was also the item of the night to purchase, so someone really miscalculated the number needed and larger sizes.   I hear the complaint from my daughter that the store is lacking women's clothing.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: I have been a member since the first year and I plan to stay a Fire fan. The parking adds made it easy to put down the deposit, since that is a large cost to attending games.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: If you are going to give a season ticket holder package, make it something we can use, except another scarf. One year we got Adidas backpacks which was very nice.  Little was done for the 25th anniversary of the team or the season ticket holders who were around for all those years. For the 20th we received Adidas running tops.  I don't know if you guarantee STH of the things being handed out at games, but guaranteed getting the item of the day when entering would be nice.  How about a discount on the new Red Jerseys for STH, since we have been waiting a long time to see the men in Red. Would have been nice to have the red jerseys for xmas gifts, my two adult kids are also avid Fire fans, grew up cheering on the team and looking to get their new red jerseys.  Lastly, I still believe we can put the right team on the field and compete again for the MLS trophy.

COMMENTS__C: It's normally nowhere near busy enough where entering is an issue. I can't imagine I will use a member's only entrance if it's out of the way. I enter via the south gate because it's closest to parking and the shuttle bus dropoff, and there are never any lines.
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: "Typical stadium over-pricing for food and drinks. I'm used to it in American sports but it is not good value. The staff is generally great, particularly in the Midway. Everything else is subpar. Regular concessions stands have very poor quality food, and there are very few specialty food areas (and those that do exist in SF are not all open on Fire match days). It shocks me that we live in such an incredible food city and have pretty much zero on-site collaborations with Chicago chefs and restaurants. We also have pretty much no ""beer garden"" or cool viewing/drinking area (could be a great collaboration with a local brewery). Almost every other Chicago sports venues has much better food and beverage options."
MERCHANDISE_COMMENTS__C: I do not shop for merchandise on-site enough to have a well-rounded opinion on this.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: I love this sport, this city and this club. I want to continue supporting it so that future generations will have a chance to fall in love like I have. I also like to spend time on the lakeshore in the summer. It's a beautiful home.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: My member representative left around the middle of the season last year. He was incredibly helpful and a great asset for the club. I'm disappointed that he left. I'm more disappointed that I was not given any advance notice, and that a new representative did not reach out to me immediately to introduce themselves. I found out via his voicemail when trying to call him for help on a match day. I still do not know who my new member representative is, and I do not believe they've made any direct efforts to contact me/introduce themselves to me. I understand there was significant turnover in the ticket sales department last year. I think the club should do some serious soul searching on corporate culture and the extent to which they are creating an atmosphere which incentivizes high-performing, well-liked representatives to stick around. I would also expect a better, more personalized effort to keep members like myself satisfied and connected. The poor performance of the club and the lack of ambition on soccer-side hirings in recent weeks is weighing on dedicated season ticket holders (including myself), and we should not be taken for granted. I know most of us which much prefer a competitive team and a great stadium atmosphere over more member benefits.

CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: the food really is a hit or a miss.
MERCHANDISE_COMMENTS__C: my only purchase in 2023 was the white t-shirt with the old Fire logo in the Championship rings. the vintage look was cool.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: The only sport I consume is soccer. I could care less about the Sox, Cubs, Bulls, Bears, Hawks, etc. Mainly Liga MX, MLS, USMNT, and Mexico NT. Since the European schedule is not convenient to me, I give up a EPL and La Liga quality for convenience. CONCACAF and CONMEBOL tournaments are pretty much what keeps in engaged throughout the season. So my ability to *hopefully* experience that in Chicago is the chance I take when renewing my season tickets. For example, the best stadium atmosphere besides the Messi game, was versus Puebla and America. I have had the privilege of attending soccer games across the world, WC 2014, 2018 and Women's WC 2019. I have been to Champions League and EPL games in England. And matches at Azteca, Guadalajara, and Monterrey. I strive to someday live that experience in my seat at Soldier Field on a consistent basis. I mean the fact that Chicago isn't hosting a WC26 or Copa America 24 match is bonkers.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: US Open Cup. Anytime an MLS team plays versus a non-MLS team, that game needs to be hosted at the non-MLS team stadium. I as a season ticket holder, would certainly enjoy travelling to Milwaukee, Madison, Iowa, Indy or Detroit to name a few. It creates memories for the club.

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: The super expensive aspect has been addressed by adding back in parking taken away from the STHs who hold two or more seats. Parking remains a burden though due to taking too long, because of inefficiency of those directing paring.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: We have been STHs for awhile now and enjoy watching live soccer locally.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: Since the Fire brought in the new President of Business Operations, Dave Baldwin, it has become clear the greater interest is in making money rather than actually growing the clubâ€™s fan base, and this includes a focus on your existing most dependable fans, STHs. Iâ€™m sure itâ€™s great that Mr. Baldwin can tout his previous experience selling suites and boxes to the wealthy in his prior roles, but when you look around the league, the teams bringing in consistent and excited crowds (Atlanta, Cincinnati, St. Louis, Austin) do so because they have passionate fans for the club. And consistent crowds ensure consistent revenue; not gouging fans to see Messi and making that game more about the other player than your own (very struggling team). Itâ€™s also clear the plan is to keep raising prices, which comes as doubly difficult to swallow, segueing into the next issue.  More troublesome have been the Fireâ€™s decisions since failing to qualify for the playoffs yet again. I believe the owner truly does have the best interests of the Fire and has invested an immense amount of his own money, but it is baffling, truly baffling that a man who built his fortune on savvy business decisions can justify keeping Georg Heitz in role when in Heitzâ€™s 3.5 years so far he has unilaterally failed at his job. The Fire have had one of the highest wage bills in the league and yet, having nothing to show for it. We have not had a successful DP since before Heitzâ€™ tenure and his TAM and GAM spending decisions have resulted in us paying guaranteed huge salaries to players who are ineffective, while underpaying our performing youth. Then, as quintessential as Frank Klopas is to this team and as much as he should be a part of the team, a long term head coach he is not. Failing to capitalize on having nearly six months to find a strong coach is yet another misstep. As a fan, it is understandable that there are ups and downs and change can take time, but making the same decision over and over and expecting something different merely means youâ€™re complacent with what you have.  I would like to see the Fire focus on understanding why it cannot tap the huge soccer fan base in Chicago, and hand-in-hand with that, improve the actual quality of the team. When you do those things, that is how you build a business. When you focus purely on profit, that is how you lose your fans.  All of that to say, we will keep our season tickets this year, but are seriously considering dropping them in future years. We want to support our local club and love going to games, but canâ€™t continue to get behind a sinking ship, both from the business side of the house and the on-the-field product.

COMMENTS__C: It's frequently disappointing how often special giveaways are out of stock by the time you get to the stadium, even if it's an hour before, and then you see people walking around with multiples of the items stuffed in their bags. Beyond that the entrance is broadly fine, and efficient. The introduction of barriers and greater direction this year helped.
CONCESSIONS_COMMENTS__C: "With the discount the value can be ok. There's a general disinterest from a lot of the servers, and the machines often break. So there's been multiple times where the scanner for the concession discount is broken, and there's no attempt to help you receive the discount. It's a general, ""it's broken, don't know if it works anywhere else, you're paying full price then right"" and no particular help to resolve it. Often just have to walk away, even after waiting in line for a long time."
MERCHANDISE_COMMENTS__C: The variety is fine, price is expensive but to be expected. There's always confusion about the wintrust discount across staff.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: You have moments like the Inter Miami game where everything comes together and it feels like it matters to the staff, the organization and beyond that really feels like its important that you want to come back. I like watching soccer, and like supporting my local team.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: I wanted to clarify a few points. Adrian is lovely, and polite, can tell he's just new to the role. Eric was the gold standard for me, he'd call just to see how things were and check it and it was always appreciated. As a rep, he was thoughtful engaged, and I've enjoyed my brief interactions with Adrian so far, but I went the majority of the year without a rep, and it's just felt like year on year, that connection with them has just diminished. As if interactions are more transactional than supportive.  My number 1 complain this year, is how the club responds to the games scheduled in Bridgeview. I'm a long term season ticket holder, and a public transport user who doesn't drive and the club does nothing to help me attend games when they're moved. In previous years there was the pub to pitch program, or the Pace operated Midway to Bridgeview shuttle bus, and they were fantastic, but neither of them run now, and every time they move a game, there's always little to no clarity on whether they'll bring back pub to pitch, and most reps (not Adrian) didn't have a clue. Nor did they have any guidance on how to actually get to the stadium. Nor any follow up, or any support. It was just an attitude, of, oh well nothing I can do, and not supportive at all. It's always deeply frustrating, and massively puts me off any rescheduled game.   The second complaint, is that the restricting of fantastic supporters perks like the bike valet, which is a wonderful program to those who are only in the supporters section is ridiculous. To pay more money, to have a restricted service is deeply disappointing. I broadly use divvy, when cycling in the summer, so I get by cycling to games, but just sad not being able to share in it if I wanted to cycle on my own by to the stadium.   But beyond that, game day experience has improved immensely, beyond some retail staff, and Monterey aggression, most if not all Fire staff have always been kind and it's always been appreciated.

PARKING_COMMENTS__C: All of my problems were solved when I started parking in the North lot. When heading northbound on LSD, the North Lot entrance off of McFetridge Dr is only a few hundred feet from the corner and is generally traffic free. The Waldron Deck & South lots are absolute nightmares. The city attendants directing traffic there are often belligerent  and careless. While I don't expect us to become best friends, I do expect a general sense of respect that comes w/ positions in public service.
LONG_TEXT_1__C: I'm a fan of the Chicago Fire. I enjoy watching professional soccer live. The Bridgeview stadium is significantly closer to where I live but even in dealing w/ Soldier Field, the value I get is still worth it.
LONG_TEXT_2__C: I both see and appreciate the efforts everyone is putting into making the gameday experience better. It's not lost on me.
